    <section class="guide-body">

      <p>
        The majority of Main Street business acquisitions — those with purchase prices under $5M —
        are financed through SBA 7(a) loans. Understanding how SBA financing works is not optional
        for a seller: it directly determines your pool of qualified buyers, the maximum supportable
        price for your business, and what documentation you need to provide during diligence.
      </p>
      <p>
        Sellers who understand SBA financing sell faster at higher prices, because they can prepare
        their financials to meet SBA underwriting standards rather than discovering the issues during
        diligence — when it's too late.
      </p>

      <h2>How SBA 7(a) Acquisition Financing Works</h2>
      <p>
        The SBA 7(a) program guarantees a portion of the loan (up to 85%), which enables SBA-approved
        lenders to offer acquisition financing with:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Down payments as low as 10% of the purchase price</li>
        <li>Loan amounts up to $5,000,000</li>
        <li>Repayment terms up to 10 years for business acquisitions (25 years if real estate is included)</li>
        <li>Variable or fixed interest rates (typically Prime + 2.25% to 2.75% as of Q4 2025)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        For a $600,000 business acquisition, a buyer using SBA 7(a) financing would put down $60,000
        (10%), borrow $540,000 at approximately 10.5% over 10 years, and make monthly payments of
        approximately $7,300 ($87,600 annually). The business must generate sufficient SDE to cover
        these payments with a safety margin.
      </p>

      <h2>The Debt Service Coverage Ratio (DSCR)</h2>
      <p>
        The most important concept for sellers to understand: SBA lenders require a Debt Service
        Coverage Ratio (DSCR) of at least 1.25×. This means the business's SDE must equal at least
        1.25× the annual loan payments.
      </p>
      <div class="formula-block">
        <p><strong>DSCR = Annual SDE ÷ Annual Debt Service</strong></p>
        <p>Required: DSCR ≥ 1.25×</p>
      </div>
      <p>
        This formula effectively establishes the maximum supportable price for your business.
        Working backward from a $200,000 SDE:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Required DSCR: 1.25×</li>
        <li>Maximum annual debt service: $200,000 ÷ 1.25 = $160,000</li>
        <li>Maximum loan amount (at 10.5%, 10 years): approximately $960,000</li>
        <li>With 10% down: maximum total purchase price supported ≈ $1,067,000</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        An asking price above $1,067,000 on $200,000 SDE cannot be fully SBA-financed — the lender's
        DSCR requirement won't be met. The buyer would need a larger down payment, seller financing,
        or a cash component to bridge the gap. Understanding this math before setting your price prevents
        the most common deal failure: a price that was agreed on LOI but couldn't be financed.
      </p>

      <h2>What SBA Lenders Scrutinize</h2>
      <p>
        Beyond the DSCR, SBA lenders conduct detailed underwriting of the business. As a seller,
        expect the following to be reviewed:
      </p>

      <h3>3 Years of Business Tax Returns</h3>
      <p>
        SBA lenders reconcile the SDE claimed in the purchase agreement against the tax returns.
        Add-backs that are not supported by the returns or cannot be independently verified will not
        be counted in the DSCR calculation. A $50,000 undocumented add-back that reduces the lender's
        recognized SDE from $200,000 to $150,000 changes the maximum supportable loan significantly.
      </p>

      <h3>Customer Concentration</h3>
      <p>
        SBA lenders flag customer concentration above 20% of revenue as a risk factor. Above 30%,
        lenders typically require an explanation and sometimes a holdback or reduced loan-to-value.
        Buyers purchasing businesses with high customer concentration may be required to put down more
        than 10%. Sellers with concentrated revenue should address this before listing — see
        <a href="/guides/how-to-prepare-business-for-sale/">How to Prepare Your Business for Sale</a>.
      </p>

      <h3>Owner Dependency</h3>
      <p>
        SBA lenders evaluate whether the business will continue generating the claimed SDE after the
        current owner exits. A business where the owner is the sole service provider, holds all key
        relationships, or manages all operations personally is a higher risk — the earnings may not
        transfer to a new owner at the same level. Lenders may require longer training and transition
        periods, earnout provisions, or more conservative SDE figures.
      </p>

      <h3>Industry Type</h3>
      <p>
        Certain industries face additional SBA scrutiny or restrictions. Businesses primarily engaged in
        lending, life insurance sales, or certain real estate activities are not eligible. Restaurants
        face stricter underwriting due to historically higher failure rates. Cannabis businesses are
        not eligible for SBA financing in any form.
      </p>

      <h2>What This Means for Your Asking Price</h2>
      <p>
        The SBA DSCR formula creates an effective price ceiling for SBA-financed transactions.
        Knowing this ceiling before setting your price — rather than discovering it during financing
        review — is essential. The <a href="/">valuation calculator</a> produces a range based on
        industry transaction data. SBA financing math provides a separate check on whether that range
        is financeable.
      </p>
      <p>
        As a practical rule, the maximum SBA-supportable price is approximately 4.5–5× SDE at current
        interest rates (Q4 2025). A business with $200,000 SDE can support an SBA-financed transaction
        of approximately $900,000–$1,000,000. A business priced above that requires cash buyers, PE
        buyers, or substantial seller financing.
      </p>

      <h2>How to Make Your Business SBA-Financeable</h2>
      <p>
        Three years before going to market:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>File accurate tax returns that reflect your actual SDE, with documented add-backs</li>
        <li>Reduce customer concentration below 20% where possible</li>
        <li>Document systems and reduce owner dependency so the lender's risk assessment is favorable</li>
        <li>Maintain consistent or growing SDE — lenders use a 3-year average weighted toward recent years</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <a href="/guides/preparing-financials-for-sale/">Preparing Your Financials for a Business Sale</a>
        covers the specific documents SBA lenders require and how to prepare each one.
      </p>

